# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: passkeys
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The **FIDO** (**Fast IDentity Online**) **Alliance** is an open industry association launched in February 2013 whose stated mission is to develop and promote authentication standards that "help reduce the world’s over-reliance on passwords".
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] FIDO addresses the lack of interoperability among devices that use strong authentication and reduces the problems users face creating and remembering multiple usernames and passwords.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The USB security token device may be used to authenticate using a simple password (e.g. four-digit PIN) or by pressing a button.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The specifications emphasize a device-centric model.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] Authentication over an insecure channel happens using public-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The user's device registers the user to a server by registering a public key.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] To authenticate the user, the device signs a challenge from the server using the private key that it holds.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The keys on the device are unlocked by a local user gesture such as a biometric or pressing a button.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] FIDO provides two types of user experiences depending on which protocol is used.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] Both protocols define a common interface at the client for whatever local authentication method the user exercises.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The following open specifications may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for the specification known as FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The latter was formally submitted to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on November 12, 2015.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] Subsequently, the first Working Draft of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard was published on May 31, 2016.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The WebAuthn standard has been revised numerous times since then, becoming a W3C Recommendation on March 4, 2019.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol 2.0 Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] FIDO CTAP 2.0 complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the *FIDO2 Project*.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The FIDO2 Project is a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) whose goal is to create strong authentication for the web.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] At its core, FIDO2 consists of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol 2 (CTAP2).
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] FIDO2 is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] Taken together, WebAuthn and CTAP specify a standard authentication protocol where the protocol endpoints consist of a user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) and a WebAuthn Relying Party (also called a FIDO2 server).
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] A web user agent (i.e., a web browser) together with a WebAuthn client form an intermediary between the authenticator and the relying party.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] A single WebAuthn client Device may support multiple WebAuthn clients.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] For example, a laptop may support multiple clients, one for each conforming user agent running on the laptop.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] A conforming user agent implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] As its name implies, the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) enables a conforming cryptographic authenticator to interoperate with a WebAuthn client.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions called CTAP1/U2F and CTAP2.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] An authenticator that implements one of these protocols is typically referred to as a U2F authenticator or a FIDO2 authenticator, respectively.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] A FIDO2 authenticator that also implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:passkeys/fido-alliance] The invention of using a smartphone as a cryptographic authenticator on a computer network is claimed in US patent 7,366,913 filed in 2002.
[src:passkeys/passkey] To use WebAuthn, users require a compatible authenticator.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The standard does not specify how to store the keys required for signing, so a variety of authenticator types can be used.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The most common authenticator type is a platform authenticator, which is built into the operating system of the device.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Common platform authenticators include Android, Apple Keychain and Windows Hello.
[src:passkeys/passkey] These make use of hardware security features (such as TEE and TPM), and often sync credentials between devices for ease-of-use.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Another common authenticator type is a roaming authenticator, where a separate hardware device authenticates the user by connecting over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:passkeys/passkey] Most smartphones can be used as roaming authenticators, and dedicated physical security keys are also used.
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn is effectively backward compatible with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) as they both use the CTAP protocol.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Password managers can also be used as an authenticator, often with cloud sync.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Where credentials sync is not viable or possible, WebAuthn Hybrid Transport can be used to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Like legacy U2F, WebAuthn is resistant to some phishing attacks as the authenticator only offers credentials that were registered on the same website.
[src:passkeys/passkey] However, unlike U2F, WebAuthn can be implemented in a passwordless manner.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Moreover, a roaming hardware authenticator resists malware, since the keys are stored on a separate device, which prevents the malware from accessing them directly.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The WebAuthn Level 1 and 2 standards were published as W3C Recommendations on 4 March 2019 and 8 April 2021 respectively.
[src:passkeys/passkey] A Level 3 specification is currently a *First Public Working Draft* (FPWD).
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn is a core component of the FIDO2 Project under the guidance of the FIDO Alliance.
[src:passkeys/passkey] FIDO2 is the successor to FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:passkeys/passkey] Whereas U2F only supports multi-factor mode, having been designed to strengthen existing username/password-based login flows, FIDO2 adds support for single-factor mode.
[src:passkeys/passkey] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a test of *user presence*, which usually consists of a simple button push; no password is required.
[src:passkeys/passkey] In single-factor mode, the authenticator (*something you have*) performs *user verification*.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Regardless of mode, the authenticator never shares its secrets or biometric data with the website.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Moreover, a single user's secret or biometric works with all websites, as the authenticator selects the correct cryptographic key material to use for the service requesting authentication after user verification was completed successfully.
[src:passkeys/passkey] A secret and biometric on the authenticator can be used together, similarly to how they would be used on a smartphone.
[src:passkeys/passkey] For example, a fingerprint provides convenient access to user's smartphone, but occasionally fingerprint access fails, in which case user can use a PIN.
[src:passkeys/passkey] When Apple first introduced passkeys to the public in 2022, they emphasized their first-party platform integrations.
[src:passkeys/passkey] This, combined with the lack of clear communication from other industry leaders, led some to speculate that passkeys were proprietary to Apple, which was not the case.
[src:passkeys/passkey] As browsers and websites began to implement WebAuthn, the inconsistent feature-sets resulted in a variety of understandings of what exactly counted as a passkey.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Some people assumed that a passkey required management by a platform authenticator, or needed synchronization using the cloud.
[src:passkeys/passkey] A better definition is that a passkey is any WebAuthn credential managed by any WebAuthn authenticator.
[src:passkeys/passkey] This definition covers most of what different vendors refer to and accept as *passkeys*.
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn specifies how a claimant demonstrates possession and control of a FIDO2 authenticator to a verifier called the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The authentication process is mediated by an entity called the WebAuthn Client, which is little more than a conforming web browser.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Authenticator is a multi-factor cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography to sign an authentication assertion targeted at the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Assuming the authenticator uses either a facial recognition, fingerprint or PIN for user verification, the authenticator itself is *something you have* while the facial recognition and fingerprint (biometric) are *something you are* and the PIN is *something you know*.
[src:passkeys/passkey] To initiate the WebAuthn authentication flow, the WebAuthn Relying Party indicates its intentions to the WebAuthn Client (i.e., the browser) via JavaScript.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The WebAuthn Client communicates with the authenticator using a JavaScript API implemented in the browser.
[src:passkeys/passkey] A roaming authenticator conforms to the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP), and connected over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn does not strictly require a roaming hardware authenticator.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Alternatively, a software authenticator (e.g., implemented on a smartphone) or a platform authenticator (i.e., an authenticator implemented directly on the WebAuthn Client Device) may be used.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Relevant examples of platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn Hybrid Transport allows the WebAuthn Client to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone, useful in certain situations where credential sync is not viable.
[src:passkeys/passkey] There is a lingering misunderstanding among users that biometric data is transmitted over the network in the same manner as passwords, which is not the case.
[src:passkeys/passkey] When the WebAuthn Relying Party receives the signed authentication assertion from the browser, the digital signature on the assertion is verified using a trusted public key for the user.
[src:passkeys/passkey] To obtain a public key for the user, the WebAuthn Relying Party initiates a WebAuthn registration flow that is similar to the authentication flow illustrated above.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The primary difference is that the authenticator now signs an attestation statement with its attestation private key.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The signed attestation statement contains a copy of the public key that the WebAuthn Relying Party ultimately uses to verify a signed authentication assertion.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The attestation certificate contains metadata describing the authenticator itself.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The digital signature on the attestation statement is verified with the trusted attestation public key for that particular model of authenticator.
[src:passkeys/passkey] How the WebAuthn Relying Party obtains its store of trusted attestation public keys is unspecified.
[src:passkeys/passkey] One option is to use the FIDO metadata service.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The attestation type specified in the JavaScript determines the trust model.
[src:passkeys/passkey] For instance, an attestation type called self-attestation may be desired, for which the trust model is essentially trust on first use.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The WebAuthn Level 1 standard was published as a W3C Recommendation by the Web Authentication Working Group on 4 March 2019.
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn is supported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari and Opera.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The desktop version of Google Chrome has supported WebAuthn since version 67.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Firefox, which had not fully supported the previous FIDO U2F standard, included and enabled WebAuthn in Firefox version 60, released on 9 May 2018.
[src:passkeys/passkey] An early Windows Insider release of Microsoft Edge (Build 17682) implemented a version of WebAuthn that works with both Windows Hello as well as external security keys.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Existing FIDO U2F security keys are largely compatible with the WebAuthn standard, though WebAuthn added the ability to reference a unique per-account "user handle" identifier, which older authenticators are unable to store.
[src:passkeys/passkey] One of the first FIDO2-compatible authenticators was the second-generation Security Key by Yubico, announced on 10 April 2018.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The first FIDO2-compatible authenticators with a display was Trezor Model T by SatoshiLabs, announced on 6 November 2019.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Trezor Model T was also the first authenticator that allowed users to select which FIDO2 resident credential should be used directly on a device.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The first Security Level 2 certified FIDO2 key, called "Goldengate" was announced one year later by eWBM on 8 April 2019.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Dropbox announced support for WebAuthn logins (as a 2nd factor) on 8 May 2018.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Apple announced that Face ID or Touch ID could be used as a WebAuthn platform authenticator with Safari on 24 June 2020.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Several password managers such as Bitwarden and Dashlane support WebAuthn.
[src:passkeys/passkey] WebAuthn implements an extension of the W3C's more general Credential Management API, which is an attempt to formalize the interaction between websites and web browsers when exchanging user credentials.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The Web Authentication API extends the Credential Management `navigator.credentials.create()` and `navigator.credentials.get()` JavaScript methods so they accept a `publicKey` parameter.
[src:passkeys/passkey] To check if a browser supports WebAuthn, scripts should check if the `window.PublicKeyCredential` interface is defined.
[src:passkeys/passkey] In addition to `PublicKeyCredential`, the standard also defines the `AuthenticatorResponse`, `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`, and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` interfaces in addition to a variety of dictionaries and other datatypes.
[src:passkeys/passkey] The API does not allow direct access to or manipulation of private keys, beyond requesting their initial creation.
[src:passkeys/passkey] In August 2018, Paragon Initiative Enterprises conducted a security audit of the WebAuthn standard.
[src:passkeys/passkey] While they could not find any specific exploits, they revealed some serious weaknesses in the way the underlying cryptography is used and mandated by the standard.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Paragon Initiative Enterprises also criticized how the standard was initially developed, as the proposal was not made public in advance and experienced cryptographers were not asked for suggestions and feedback.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Hence the standard was not subject to broad cryptographic research from the academic world.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Despite these shortcomings, Paragon Initiative Enterprises still encourage users to continue to use WebAuthn but have come up with some recommendations for potential implementers and developers of the standard that they hope can be implemented before the standard is finalized.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Avoiding such mistakes as early as possible would protect the industry from any challenges that are introduced by broken standards and the need for backwards compatibility.
[src:passkeys/passkey] ECDAA was only designed to use in combination with device attestation.
[src:passkeys/passkey] This particular feature of WebAuthn is not necessarily required for authentication to work.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Current implementations allow the user to decide whether an attestation statement is sent during the registration ceremony.
[src:passkeys/passkey] Independently, relying parties can choose to require attestation or not.
[src:passkeys/passkey] ECDAA was removed from WebAuthn Level 2 as it was not implemented by browsers nor relying parties.
[src:passkeys/password] A **password**, sometimes called a **passcode**, is secret data, typically a string of characters, usually used to confirm a user's identity.
[src:passkeys/password] Traditionally, passwords were expected to be memorized, but the large number of password-protected services that a typical individual accesses can make memorization of unique passwords for each service impractical.
[src:passkeys/password] Using the terminology of the NIST Digital Identity Guidelines, the secret is held by a party called the *claimant* while the party verifying the identity of the claimant is called the *verifier*.
[src:passkeys/password] When the claimant successfully demonstrates knowledge of the password to the verifier through an established authentication protocol, the verifier can infer the claimant's identity.
[src:passkeys/password] In general, a password is a sequence of characters including letters, digits, or other symbols.
[src:passkeys/password] If the permissible characters are constrained to be numeric, the corresponding secret is sometimes called a personal identification number (PIN).
[src:passkeys/password] Despite its name, a password does not need to be an actual word; indeed, a non-word (in the dictionary sense) may be harder to guess, which is a desirable property of passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] A memorized secret consisting of a sequence of words or other text separated by spaces is sometimes called a passphrase.
[src:passkeys/password] A passphrase is similar to a password in usage, but the former is generally longer for added security.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords have been used since ancient times.
[src:passkeys/password] Sentries would challenge those wishing to enter an area to supply a password or *watchword*, and would only allow a person or group to pass if they knew the password.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords in military use evolved to include not just a password, but a password and a counterpassword; for example in the opening days of the Battle of Normandy, paratroopers of the U.S.
[src:passkeys/password] 101st Airborne Division used a password—*flash*—which was presented as a challenge, and answered with the correct response—*thunder*.
[src:passkeys/password] The challenge and response were changed every three days.
[src:passkeys/password] American paratroopers also famously used a device known as a "cricket" on D-Day in place of a password system as a temporarily unique method of identification; one metallic click given by the device in lieu of a password was to be met by two clicks in reply.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords have been used with computers since the earliest days of computing.
[src:passkeys/password] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), an operating system introduced at MIT in 1961, was the first computer system to implement password login.
[src:passkeys/password] CTSS had a LOGIN command that requested a user password.
[src:passkeys/password] "After typing PASSWORD, the system turns off the printing mechanism, if possible, so that the user may type in his password with privacy." In the early 1970s, Robert Morris developed a system of storing login passwords in a hashed form as part of the Unix operating system.
[src:passkeys/password] The system was based on a simulated Hagelin rotor crypto machine, and first appeared in 6th Edition Unix in 1974.
[src:passkeys/password] A later version of his algorithm, known as crypt(3), used a 12-bit salt and invoked a modified form of the DES algorithm 25 times to reduce the risk of pre-computed dictionary attacks.
[src:passkeys/password] In modern times, user names and passwords are commonly used by people during a log in process that controls access to protected computer operating systems, mobile phones, cable TV decoders, automated teller machines (ATMs), etc.
[src:passkeys/password] A typical computer user has passwords for multiple purposes: logging into accounts, retrieving e-mail, accessing applications, databases, networks, websites, and even reading the morning newspaper online.
[src:passkeys/password] Generally, the easier a password is for the owner to remember, the easier it is for an attacker to guess.
[src:passkeys/password] Similarly, the more stringent the password requirements, such as "have a mix of uppercase and lowercase letters and digits" or "change it monthly", the greater the degree to which users will subvert the system.
[src:passkeys/password] Others argue longer passwords provide more security (e.g., entropy) than shorter passwords with a wide variety of characters.
[src:passkeys/password] In *The Memorability and Security of Passwords*, Jeff Yan et al. examine the effect of advice given to users about a good choice of password.
[src:passkeys/password] They found that passwords based on thinking of a phrase and taking the first letter of each word are just as memorable as naively selected passwords, and just as hard to crack as randomly generated passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] Combining two or more unrelated words and altering some of the letters to special characters or numbers is another good method, but a single dictionary word is not.
[src:passkeys/password] Having a personally designed algorithm for generating obscure passwords is another good method.
[src:passkeys/password] Asking users to use "both letters and digits" will often lead to easy-to-guess substitutions such as 'E' → '3' and 'I' → '1', substitutions that are well known to attackers.
[src:passkeys/password] Similarly typing the password one keyboard row higher is a common trick known to attackers.
[src:passkeys/password] Traditional advice to memorize passwords and never write them down has become a challenge because of the sheer number of passwords users of computers and the internet are expected to maintain.
[src:passkeys/password] One survey concluded that the average user has around 100 passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] To manage the proliferation of passwords, some users employ the same password for multiple accounts, a dangerous practice since a data breach in one account could compromise the rest.
[src:passkeys/password] Less risky alternatives include the use of password managers, single sign-on systems and simply keeping paper lists of less critical passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] Such practices can reduce the number of passwords that must be memorized, such as the password manager's master password, to a more manageable number.
[src:passkeys/password] The security of a password-protected system depends on several factors.
[src:passkeys/password] The overall system must be designed for sound security, with protection against computer viruses, man-in-the-middle attacks and the like.
[src:passkeys/password] Physical security issues are also a concern, from deterring shoulder surfing to more sophisticated physical threats such as video cameras and keyboard sniffers.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords should be chosen so that they are hard for an attacker to guess and hard for an attacker to discover using any of the available automatic attack schemes.
[src:passkeys/password] Nowadays, it is a common practice for computer systems to hide passwords as they are typed.
[src:passkeys/password] The purpose of this measure is to prevent bystanders from reading the password; however, some argue that this practice may lead to mistakes and stress, encouraging users to choose weak passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] As an alternative, users should have the option to show or hide passwords as they type them.
[src:passkeys/password] Effective access control provisions may force extreme measures on criminals seeking to acquire a password or biometric token.
[src:passkeys/password] Less extreme measures include extortion, rubber hose cryptanalysis, and side channel attack.
[src:passkeys/password] Some specific password management issues that must be considered when thinking about, choosing, and handling a password follow.
[src:passkeys/password] The rate at which an attacker can submit guessed passwords to the system is a key factor in determining system security.
[src:passkeys/password] Some systems impose a time-out of several seconds after a small number (e.g., three) of failed password entry attempts, also known as throttling.
[src:passkeys/password] In the absence of other vulnerabilities, such systems can be effectively secure with relatively simple passwords if they have been well chosen and are not easily guessed.
[src:passkeys/password] Many systems store a cryptographic hash of the password.
[src:passkeys/password] If an attacker gets access to the file of hashed passwords guessing can be done offline, rapidly testing candidate passwords against the true password's hash value.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords that are used to generate cryptographic keys (e.g., for disk encryption or Wi-Fi security) can also be subjected to high-rate guessing, known as password cracking.
[src:passkeys/password] Lists of common passwords are widely available and can make password attacks efficient.
[src:passkeys/password] Security in such situations depends on using passwords or passphrases of adequate complexity, making such an attack computationally infeasible for the attacker.
[src:passkeys/password] Some systems, such as PGP and Wi-Fi WPA, apply a computation-intensive hash to the password to slow such attacks, in a technique known as key stretching.
[src:passkeys/password] An alternative to limiting the rate at which an attacker can make guesses on a password is to limit the total number of guesses that can be made.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords entered into certain computer systems are saved in plaintext, which means they are not encrypted or protected in any way.
[src:passkeys/password] The system merely compares the password entered by the user with this unprotected list when they log in.
[src:passkeys/password] This method is extremely dangerous because anyone who manages to access the password storage can see every user's password right away.
[src:passkeys/password] That jeopardizes every account on the system.
[src:passkeys/password] Additionally, accounts belonging to users who have reused their passwords on other websites or services may also be compromised, which could result in a much larger security breach.
[src:passkeys/password] More secure systems store each password in a cryptographically protected form, so access to the actual password will still be difficult for a snooper who gains internal access to the system, while validation of user access attempts remains possible.
[src:passkeys/password] The most secure do not store passwords at all, but use a one-way derivation, such as a polynomial, modulus, or an advanced hash function.
[src:passkeys/password] Roger Needham invented the now-common approach of storing only a "hashed" form of the plaintext password.
[src:passkeys/password] When a user types in a password on such a system, the password handling software runs through a cryptographic hash algorithm, and if the hash value generated from the user's entry matches the hash stored in the password database, the user is permitted access.
[src:passkeys/password] The hash value is created by applying a cryptographic hash function to a string consisting of the submitted password and, in multiple implementations, another value known as a salt.
[src:passkeys/password] A salt prevents attackers from easily building a list of hash values for common passwords and prevents password cracking efforts from scaling across all users.
[src:passkeys/password] MD5 and SHA1 are frequently used cryptographic hash functions, but they are not recommended for password hashing unless they are used as part of a larger construction such as in PBKDF2.
[src:passkeys/password] The stored data—sometimes called the "password verifier" or the "password hash"—is often stored in Modular Crypt Format or RFC 2307 hash format, sometimes in the /etc/passwd file or the /etc/shadow file.
[src:passkeys/password] The main storage methods for passwords are plain text, hashed, hashed and salted, and reversibly encrypted.
[src:passkeys/password] If an attacker gains access to the password file, then if it is stored as plain text, no cracking is necessary.
[src:passkeys/password] If it is hashed but not salted then it is vulnerable to rainbow table attacks (which are more efficient than cracking).
[src:passkeys/password] If it is reversibly encrypted then if the attacker gets the decryption key along with the file no cracking is necessary, while if he fails to get the key cracking is not possible.
[src:passkeys/password] Thus, of the common storage formats for passwords only when passwords have been salted and hashed is cracking both necessary and possible.
[src:passkeys/password] If a cryptographic hash function is well designed, it is computationally infeasible to reverse the function to recover a plaintext password.
[src:passkeys/password] An attacker can, however, use widely available tools to attempt to guess the passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] These tools work by hashing possible passwords and comparing the result of each guess to the actual password hashes.
[src:passkeys/password] If the attacker finds a match, they know that their guess is the actual password for the associated user.
[src:passkeys/password] Password cracking tools can operate by brute force (i.e. trying every possible combination of characters) or by hashing every word from a list; large lists of possible passwords in multiple languages are widely available on the Internet.
[src:passkeys/password] The existence of password cracking tools allows attackers to easily recover poorly chosen passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] In particular, attackers can quickly recover passwords that are short, dictionary words, simple variations on dictionary words, or that use easily guessable patterns.
[src:passkeys/password] A modified version of the DES algorithm was used as the basis for the password hashing algorithm in early Unix systems.
[src:passkeys/password] The crypt algorithm used a 12-bit salt value so that each user's hash was unique and iterated the DES algorithm 25 times to make the hash function slower, both measures intended to frustrate automated guessing attacks.
[src:passkeys/password] The user's password was used as a key to encrypt a fixed value.
[src:passkeys/password] More recent Unix or Unix-like systems (e.g., Linux or the various BSD systems) use more secure password hashing algorithms such as PBKDF2, bcrypt, and scrypt, which have large salts and an adjustable cost or number of iterations.
[src:passkeys/password] A poorly designed hash function can make attacks feasible even if a strong password is chosen.
[src:passkeys/password] LM hash is a widely deployed and insecure example.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords are vulnerable to interception (i.e., "snooping") while being transmitted to the authenticating machine or person.
[src:passkeys/password] If the password is carried as electrical signals on unsecured physical wiring between the user access point and the central system controlling the password database, it is subject to snooping by wiretapping methods.
[src:passkeys/password] If it is carried as packeted data over the Internet, anyone able to watch the packets containing the logon information can snoop with a low probability of detection.
[src:passkeys/password] Email is sometimes used to distribute passwords but this is generally an insecure method.
[src:passkeys/password] Since most email is sent as plaintext, a message containing a password is readable without effort during transport by any eavesdropper.
[src:passkeys/password] Further, the message will be stored as plaintext on at least two computers: the sender's and the recipient's.
[src:passkeys/password] If it passes through intermediate systems during its travels, it will probably be stored on them as well, at least for some time, and may be copied to backup, cache or history files on any of these systems.
[src:passkeys/password] Using client-side encryption will only protect transmission from the mail handling system server to the client machine.
[src:passkeys/password] Previous or subsequent relays of the email will not be protected and the email will probably be stored on multiple computers, certainly on the originating and receiving computers, most often in clear text.
[src:passkeys/password] The risk of interception of passwords sent over the Internet can be reduced by, among other approaches, using cryptographic protection.
[src:passkeys/password] The most widely used is the Transport Layer Security (TLS, previously called SSL) feature built into most current Internet browsers.
[src:passkeys/password] Most browsers alert the user of a TLS/SSL-protected exchange with a server by displaying a closed lock icon, or some other sign, when TLS is in use.
[src:passkeys/password] There are several other techniques in use.
[src:passkeys/password] There is a conflict between stored hashed-passwords and hash-based challenge–response authentication; the latter requires a client to prove to a server that they know what the shared secret (i.e., password) is, and to do this, the server must be able to obtain the shared secret from its stored form.
[src:passkeys/password] On a number of systems (including Unix-type systems) doing remote authentication, the shared secret usually becomes the hashed form and has the serious limitation of exposing passwords to offline guessing attacks.
[src:passkeys/password] In addition, when the hash is used as a shared secret, an attacker does not need the original password to authenticate remotely; they only need the hash.
[src:passkeys/password] Rather than transmitting a password, or transmitting the hash of the password, password-authenticated key agreement systems can perform a zero-knowledge password proof, which proves knowledge of the password without exposing it.
[src:passkeys/password] Moving a step further, augmented systems for password-authenticated key agreement (e.g., AMP, B-SPEKE, PAK-Z, SRP-6) avoid both the conflict and limitation of hash-based methods.
[src:passkeys/password] An augmented system allows a client to prove knowledge of the password to a server, where the server knows only a (not exactly) hashed password, and where the unhashed password is required to gain access.
[src:passkeys/password] Usually, a system must provide a way to change a password, either because a user believes the current password has been (or might have been) compromised, or as a precautionary measure.
[src:passkeys/password] If a new password is passed to the system in unencrypted form, security can be lost (e.g., via wiretapping) before the new password can even be installed in the password database and if the new password is given to a compromised employee, little is gained.
[src:passkeys/password] Some websites include the user-selected password in an unencrypted confirmation e-mail message, with the obvious increased vulnerability.
[src:passkeys/password] Identity management systems are increasingly used to automate the issuance of replacements for lost passwords, a feature called self-service password reset.
[src:passkeys/password] The user's identity is verified by asking questions and comparing the answers to ones previously stored (i.e., when the account was opened).
[src:passkeys/password] Some password reset questions ask for personal information that could be found on social media, such as mother's maiden name.
[src:passkeys/password] As a result, some security experts recommend either making up one's own questions or giving false answers.
[src:passkeys/password] "Password aging" is a feature of some operating systems which forces users to change passwords frequently (e.g., quarterly, monthly or even more often).
[src:passkeys/password] Such policies usually provoke user protest and foot-dragging at best and hostility at worst.
[src:passkeys/password] There is often an increase in the number of people who note down the password and leave it where it can easily be found, as well as help desk calls to reset a forgotten password.
[src:passkeys/password] Users may use simpler passwords or develop variation patterns on a consistent theme to keep their passwords memorable.
[src:passkeys/password] Because of these issues, there is some debate as to whether password aging is effective.
[src:passkeys/password] Changing a password will not prevent abuse in most cases, since the abuse would often be immediately noticeable.
[src:passkeys/password] However, if someone may have had access to the password through some means, such as sharing a computer or breaching a different site, changing the password limits the window for abuse.
[src:passkeys/password] Allotting separate passwords to each user of a system is preferable to having a single password shared by legitimate users of the system, certainly from a security viewpoint.
[src:passkeys/password] This is partly because users are more willing to tell another person (who may not be authorized) a shared password than one exclusively for their use.
[src:passkeys/password] Single passwords are also much less convenient to change because multiple people need to be told at the same time, and they make removal of a particular user's access more difficult, as for instance on graduation or resignation.
[src:passkeys/password] Separate logins are also often used for accountability, for example to know who changed a piece of data.
[src:passkeys/password] Some of the more stringent policy enforcement measures can pose a risk of alienating users, possibly decreasing security as a result.
[src:passkeys/password] It is common practice amongst computer users to reuse the same password on multiple sites.
[src:passkeys/password] This presents a substantial security risk, because an attacker needs to only compromise a single site in order to gain access to other sites the victim uses.
[src:passkeys/password] This problem is exacerbated by also reusing usernames, and by websites requiring email logins, as it makes it easier for an attacker to track a single user across multiple sites.
[src:passkeys/password] Password reuse can be avoided or minimized by using mnemonic techniques, writing passwords down on paper, or using a password manager.
[src:passkeys/password] Similar arguments were made by Forbes, to not change passwords as often as some "experts" advise, due to the same limitations in human memory.
[src:passkeys/password] A study conducted by Ofcom and published on April 2, 2026, found that 26% of online adults reuse passwords, and that 13% of those adults had had their social media or email accounts hacked.
[src:passkeys/password] Historically, multiple security experts asked people to memorize their passwords: "Never write down a password".
[src:passkeys/password] More recently, multiple security experts such as Bruce Schneier recommend that people use passwords that are too complicated to memorize, write them down on paper, and keep them in a wallet.
[src:passkeys/password] Password management software can also store passwords relatively safely, in an encrypted file sealed with a single master password.
[src:passkeys/password] To facilitate estate administration, it is helpful for people to provide a mechanism for their passwords to be communicated to the persons who will administer their affairs in the event of their death.
[src:passkeys/password] Should a record of accounts and passwords be prepared, care must be taken to ensure that the records are secure, to prevent theft or fraud.
[src:passkeys/password] Multi-factor authentication schemes combine passwords (as "knowledge factors") with one or more other means of authentication to make authentication more secure and less vulnerable to compromised passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] For example, a simple two-factor login might send a text message, e-mail, automated phone call, or similar alert whenever a login attempt is made, possibly supplying a code that must be entered in addition to a password.
[src:passkeys/password] More sophisticated factors include such things as hardware tokens and biometric security.
[src:passkeys/password] Password rotation is a policy that is commonly implemented with the goal of enhancing computer security.
[src:passkeys/password] In 2019, Microsoft stated that the practice is "ancient and obsolete".
[src:passkeys/password] Some governments have national authentication frameworks that define requirements for user authentication to government services, including requirements for passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] Many websites enforce standard rules such as minimum and maximum length, but also frequently include composition rules such as featuring at least one capital letter and at least one number/symbol.
[src:passkeys/password] These latter, more specific rules were largely based on a 2003 report by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), authored by Bill Burr.
[src:passkeys/password] It originally proposed the practice of using numbers, obscure characters and capital letters and updating regularly.
[src:passkeys/password] In a 2017 article in *The Wall Street Journal*, Burr reported he regrets these proposals and made a mistake when he recommended them.
[src:passkeys/password] According to a 2017 rewrite of this NIST report, a number of websites have rules that actually have the opposite effect on the security of their users.
[src:passkeys/password] This includes complex composition rules as well as forced password changes after certain periods of time.
[src:passkeys/password] While these rules have long been widespread, they have also long been seen as annoying and ineffective by both users and cybersecurity experts.
[src:passkeys/password] The NIST recommends people use longer phrases as passwords (and advises websites to raise the maximum password length) instead of hard-to-remember passwords with "illusory complexity" such as "pA55w+rd".
[src:passkeys/password] A user prevented from using the password "password" may, if required to include a number and uppercase letter, simply choose "Password1".
[src:passkeys/password] Combined with forced periodic password changes, this can lead to passwords that are difficult to remember but easy to crack.
[src:passkeys/password] Paul Grassi, one of the 2017 NIST report's authors, further elaborated: "Everyone knows that an exclamation point is a 1, or an I, or the last character of a password. $ is an S or a 5.
[src:passkeys/password] If we use these well-known tricks, we aren't fooling any adversary.
[src:passkeys/password] Pieris Tsokkis and Eliana Stavrou were able to identify some bad password construction strategies through their research and development of a password generator tool.
[src:passkeys/password] They came up with eight categories of password construction strategies based on exposed password lists, password cracking tools, and online reports citing the most used passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] These categories include user-related information, keyboard combinations and patterns, placement strategy, word processing, substitution, capitalization, append dates, and a combination of the previous categories.
[src:passkeys/password] Attempting to crack passwords by trying as many possibilities as time and money permit is a brute-force attack.
[src:passkeys/password] A related method, rather more efficient in most cases, is a dictionary attack.
[src:passkeys/password] In a dictionary attack, all words in one or more dictionaries are tested.
[src:passkeys/password] Lists of common passwords are also typically tested.
[src:passkeys/password] Password strength is the likelihood that a password cannot be guessed or discovered, and varies with the attack algorithm used.
[src:passkeys/password] Cryptologists and computer scientists often refer to the strength or 'hardness' in terms of entropy.
[src:passkeys/password] Passwords easily discovered are termed *weak* or *vulnerable*; passwords difficult or impossible to discover are considered *strong*.
[src:passkeys/password] There are several programs available for password attack (or even auditing and recovery by systems personnel) such as L0phtCrack, John the Ripper, and Cain; some of which use password design vulnerabilities (as found in the Microsoft LANManager system) to increase efficiency.
[src:passkeys/password] These programs are sometimes used by system administrators to detect weak passwords proposed by users.
[src:passkeys/password] Studies of production computer systems have consistently shown that a large fraction of all user-chosen passwords are readily guessed automatically.
[src:passkeys/password] For example, Columbia University found 22% of user passwords could be recovered with little effort.
[src:passkeys/password] According to Bruce Schneier, examining data from a 2006 phishing attack, 55% of MySpace passwords would be crackable in 8 hours using a commercially available Password Recovery Toolkit capable of testing 200,000 passwords per second in 2006.
[src:passkeys/password] He also reported that the single most common password was *password1*, confirming yet again the general lack of informed care in choosing passwords among users.
[src:passkeys/password] The multiple ways in which permanent or semi-permanent passwords can be compromised has prompted the development of other techniques.
[src:passkeys/password] Some are inadequate in practice, and in any case few have become universally available for users seeking a more secure alternative.
[src:passkeys/password] "The password is dead" is a recurring idea in computer security.
[src:passkeys/password] The reasons given often include reference to the usability as well as security problems of passwords.
[src:passkeys/password] It often accompanies arguments that the replacement of passwords by a more secure means of authentication is both necessary and imminent.
[src:passkeys/password] This claim has been made by a number of people at least since 2004.
[src:passkeys/password] Alternatives to passwords include biometrics, two-factor authentication or single sign-on, Microsoft's Cardspace, the Higgins project, the Liberty Alliance, NSTIC, the FIDO Alliance and various Identity 2.0 proposals.
[src:passkeys/password] Bonneau et al. systematically compared web passwords to other technical solutions that were alternatives.
[src:passkeys/password] They reviewed these in respect of usability, deployability, and security.
[src:passkeys/password] Their analysis showed that most alternatives do better than passwords on security, some do better and some worse with respect to usability, while *every* alternative does worse than passwords on deployability.
[src:passkeys/password] This may be why over 20 years after this recurring idea started, passwords are still being used, despite attempts by technology businesses to change this.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Passwordless authentication methods typically rely on public-key cryptography infrastructure, where the public key is provided during registration to the authenticating service (remote server, application, or website).
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] In contrast, the private key is kept on a user’s device (PC, smartphone or an external security token) and can be accessed only by providing a biometric signature or another authentication factor which is not knowledge-based.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Some designs might also accept a combination of other factors such as geo-location, network address, behavioral patterns, and gestures, as long as no memorized passwords are involved.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Passwordless authentication is sometimes confused with multi-factor authentication (MFA), since both use a wide variety of authentication factors.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Still, while MFA is often used as an added layer of security on top of password-based authentication, passwordless authentication does not require a memorized secret.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Usually, it uses just one highly secure factor to authenticate identity (i.e., an external security token), making it faster and simpler for users.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] When both approaches are employed, “Passwordless MFA” is the term used.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] The authentication flow is passwordless and uses multiple factors, providing the highest security level when implemented correctly.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] The notion that passwords should become obsolete has been circling in computer science since at least 2004.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Avivah Litan of Gartner said in 2014, "Passwords were dead a few years ago.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Now they are more than dead." The reasons given often include reference to the usability as well as security problems of passwords.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Bonneau et al. systematically compared web passwords to 35 competing authentication schemes regarding their usability, deployability, and security.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] (The technical report is an extended version of the peer-reviewed paper by the same name.) Their analysis shows that most schemes do better than passwords on security, some schemes do better and some worse regarding usability, while *every* scheme does worse than passwords on deployability.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Recent technological advancements (e.g., the proliferation of biometric devices and smartphones) and changing business culture (acceptance of biometrics and decentralized workforce, for example) continuously promote the adoption of passwordless authentication.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] Leading tech companies (Microsoft, Google) and industry wide initiatives are developing better architectures and practices to bring it to wider use, with many taking a cautious approach, keeping passwords behind the scenes in some use cases.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] The development of open standards such as FIDO2 and WebAuthn has further generated adoption of passwordless technologies such as Windows Hello.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] On June 24, 2020, Apple Safari announced that Face ID or Touch ID would be available as a WebAuthn platform authenticator for passwordless login.
[src:passkeys/passwordless-authentication] A user must first register with a system before their identity can be verified.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:passkeys/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
